<section class="faq section-white">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="eyebrow">FAQ</span>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p>Quick answers about HR in the Netherlands.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item" open>
        <summary>How long does it take to hire an employee in the Netherlands?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Typically 2-4 weeks for the administrative setup, though this varies based on the employee's nationality and visa requirements. For EU citizens, the process is faster. For non-EU citizens requiring a Highly Skilled Migrant visa, allow 4-6 weeks.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the 30% ruling and does my company qualify?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>The 30% ruling is a Dutch tax advantage for incoming expat employees, allowing 30% of their salary to be paid tax-free. To qualify, the employee must be recruited from abroad and possess specific expertise not readily available in the Netherlands.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Do I need a Dutch entity to hire employees?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Yes, to directly employ someone in the Netherlands, you generally need a Dutch legal entity (B.V.). However, alternatives exist such as using an Employer of Record (EOR) service, which allows you to hire without entity setup.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What are the mandatory employer costs in the Netherlands?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Beyond gross salary, expect approximately 20-30% additional costs: social insurance contributions (~15-20%), mandatory pension contributions (varies by industry), 8% holiday allowance (vakantiegeld), and sick leave insurance.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How does sick leave work under Dutch law?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Dutch employers must continue paying at least 70% of an employee's salary during illness for up to 2 years (104 weeks). You're also required to follow the Wet Poortwachter reintegration process.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Can you help with urgent dismissal situations?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          <p>Absolutely — that's our HR S.O.S. service. Dutch dismissal law is complex and heavily favors employees. We provide same-day guidance and complete legal support throughout the process.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-cta">
      <span>Still have questions?</span>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Contact Our Team →</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

